## Spelling gate

Markdown prose is checked for en-GB-oxendict (Oxford "-ize") spelling with
[`typos`](https://github.com/crate-ci/typos). The gate has two layers:

- `typos.toml` is generated configuration: the `en-gb` locale corrects
  American spellings, and a generated `extend-words` table restores the
  Oxford `-ize` forms the locale would otherwise reject. Never edit its
  entries by hand.
- `scripts/generate_typos_config.py` is the single source of truth. To add
  a new Oxford `-ize` stem, accept a word verbatim, or ignore a pattern,
  edit its `STEMS`, `EXTRA_ACCEPTED_WORDS`, or `extend-ignore-re` lists and
  regenerate with `python3 scripts/generate_typos_config.py`.

`make spellcheck` first runs the generator's `--check` mode, which parses
the generated document (failing fast on duplicate keys), asserts the entry
count, and fails on drift between `typos.toml` and the generator. It then
runs `typos` over the Markdown files at the version pinned by the Makefile
`TYPOS_VERSION` variable through `uv tool run`, so local runs and CI use
the same version. `make markdownlint` depends on `make spellcheck`, and CI
runs it as a dedicated step.

Quoted APIs and identifiers keep their upstream spelling; put them in
backticks or fenced code blocks, which the spelling gate ignores, rather
than adding word-level exceptions.
